<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-389-026  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 389 026.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 22 1989 n1169 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Uncovering the cracks in the Nicholson Bill. (proposed Britishcomputer crime law)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cornwall, Hugo.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Member of Parliament Emma Nicholson's Anti-Hacking Bill isaimed at the wrong target and will be unenforceable because itfails to address the real issues in computer crime.andP;  The term'hacker' originally meant 'inventive programmer' but has becomesynonymous with system crackers and other computer criminals.andO;Security consultants seeking to market their services, panickedusers, and publicity-hungry groups are perpetuating the negativeconnotations of hacking.andP;  The Anti-Hacking bill will make it anoffense to use any equipment with the 'intent' to effect'unauthorized access,' terms which are extremely difficult todefine.andP;  Most computer crime is ordinary white-collar crime with acomputer element and requires little technical knowledge.andP;  Insideknowledge and opportunity are more important in these cases, while'unauthorized access' is merely a preparatory act.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Great Britain. Anti-Hacking Bill (Draft) (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Computer CrimesLegislationComputer HackersCommunications Tapping.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>